    difficulty: "Beginner",
    body: "Deciding when to stop driving is one of the hardest conversations many families ever have. The car represents independence, freedom, and a lifetime of going where you want when you want. Hanging up the keys can feel like giving up a piece of who you are. The honest truth is that for almost every adult who lives long enough, the day comes when driving stops being a good fit. The brain and body change with age, and so do the conditions on American roads. The trick is to look at the warning signs early, talk about them with the people you trust, and make the change on your own terms before a crash or a license suspension forces the issue.\n\nThe science on aging drivers is not as grim as the news sometimes suggests. Drivers between 65 and 75 actually have the safest crash records of any adult age group, in part because they drive fewer miles, avoid rush hour, and rarely drink and drive. The crash rate per mile starts to rise after age 75 and rises faster after age 85. The biggest risks are slower reaction time, weakened side vision, and the effects of common medications like sleep aids, blood pressure drugs, and pain pills. Most of these risks can be managed for a while with smaller, smarter driving habits. Eventually, the risks outgrow the workarounds, and the right answer is to step away.\n\nThis guide is written for both older drivers themselves and the family members who love them. We cover the early warning signs to watch for, the formal self-assessment tools that the American Automobile Association and AARP publish, the conversation to have with a primary care doctor, how to handle a family conversation that goes sideways, and the practical steps for closing out a driving life with dignity. We also include a note about the rare cases when family or a doctor must take action even though the driver disagrees, because some medical conditions remove the ability to judge the situation honestly.\n\nThe most important point is this: stopping driving is not the end of a meaningful life. Most older adults who stop driving report higher life satisfaction within a year, once the new ride routines are in place and the daily stress of driving is gone. The transition is hard for a few months, but the freedom of never worrying about traffic, parking, or a fender-bender is real. Read this guide once, then read it again with the family member you trust most. Make a plan together, on your terms, before anyone else makes the plan for you.",
